## Domain-Driven Design Principles

Domain-Driven Design models software after real-world business concepts, creating a "ubiquitous language" shared between developers and domain experts.

### Entities

Entities have a unique identifier (`id`) that distinguishes them across time, even if other attributes change.

```typescript
// Good: Candidate is an entity (unique identity, persists across operations)
export class Candidate {
    id?: number;
    firstName: string;
    lastName: string;
    email: string;
    
    constructor(data: CandidateData) {
        this.id = data.id;
        this.firstName = data.firstName;
        this.lastName = data.lastName;
        this.email = data.email;
    }
    
    // Domain logic encapsulated in the entity
    validateEmail(): void {
        if (!this.email.includes('@')) {
            throw new Error('Invalid email format');
        }
    }
}
```

**When to use entities**:
- Objects with a unique identifier that persist in the database
- Objects whose identity matters more than their attributes
- Objects that change over time but retain their identity

---

### Value Objects

Value Objects describe aspects of the domain without conceptual identity. Define and validate them immutably.

```typescript
// Example: Email as a value object (immutable, no identity)
export class Email {
    readonly value: string;
    
    constructor(value: string) {
        if (!value.includes('@')) {
            throw new Error('Invalid email format');
        }
        this.value = value;
    }
    
    equals(other: Email): boolean {
        return this.value === other.value;
    }
}
```

**Characteristics**:
- Immutable after construction
- No unique identifier (equivalence determined by attributes)
- Validated upon creation
- Use TypeScript `readonly` to enforce immutability

---

### Aggregates

Aggregates are clusters of entities and value objects treated as a single unit. An **aggregate root** enforces consistency boundaries.

```typescript
// Candidate is the aggregate root; Education and WorkExperience are owned entities
export class Candidate {
    id?: number;
    firstName: string;
    lastName: string;
    email: string;
    educations: Education[];
    workExperiences: WorkExperience[];
    
    constructor(data: CandidateData) {
        this.id = data.id;
        this.firstName = data.firstName;
        this.lastName = data.lastName;
        this.email = data.email;
        this.educations = data.educations?.map(edu => new Education(edu)) || [];
        this.workExperiences = data.workExperiences?.map(exp => new WorkExperience(exp)) || [];
    }
    
    // Aggregate root enforces consistency
    addEducation(education: Education): void {
        if (!this.email) {
            throw new Error('Cannot add education without email');
        }
        this.educations.push(education);
    }
}
```

**Guidelines**:
- Single aggregate root per use case
- Aggregates communicate through repositories, not direct references
- Internal consistency enforced in aggregate root; don't bypass it

---

### Repositories

Repositories abstract data persistence, presenting domain entities as if they were in memory.

```typescript
// Domain layer: Interface (contract)
export interface ICandidateRepository {
    findById(id: number): Promise<Candidate | null>;
    findByEmail(email: string): Promise<Candidate | null>;
    save(candidate: Candidate): Promise<Candidate>;
    delete(id: number): Promise<void>;
}

// Infrastructure layer: Implementation with Prisma
export class CandidateRepository implements ICandidateRepository {
    constructor(private prisma: PrismaClient) {}
    
    async findById(id: number): Promise<Candidate | null> {
        const data = await this.prisma.candidate.findUnique({
            where: { id },
            include: { educations: true, workExperiences: true }
        });
        return data ? new Candidate(data) : null;
    }
    
    async save(candidate: Candidate): Promise<Candidate> {
        // Use Prisma nested writes for atomic transactions
        const saved = await this.prisma.candidate.create({
            data: {
                firstName: candidate.firstName,
                lastName: candidate.lastName,
                email: candidate.email,
                educations: { create: candidate.educations },
                workExperiences: { create: candidate.workExperiences }
            }
        });
        return new Candidate(saved);
    }
}
```

**Best practices**:
- Define repository interfaces in domain layer
- Implement repositories with Prisma in infrastructure layer
- Inject repositories into services via dependency injection
- Repositories return domain entities, not raw Prisma data

