## SOLID Principles

### Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)

Each class has one reason to change.

```typescript
// Good: Candidate entity only has candidate-related logic
export class Candidate {
    validateEmail(): void { /* validation */ }
}

// Good: Repository only handles persistence
export class CandidateRepository {
    async save(candidate: Candidate): Promise<Candidate> { /* persistence */ }
}

// Good: Service orchestrates business logic
export class CandidateService {
    async create(data: CandidateData): Promise<Candidate> {
        // Orchestrate domain logic, repository calls
    }
}

// Bad: Class mixing validation, persistence, and business logic
export class CandidateProcessor {
    validate() { /* ... */ }
    save() { /* ... */ }
    calculateScore() { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

### Open/Closed Principle (OCP)

Software should be open for extension, closed for modification. Use interfaces for contracts.

```typescript
// Good: Define interfaces for contracts; implementations can extend without modifying interfaces
export interface IEmailService {
    send(to: string, subject: string, body: string): Promise<void>;
}

export class SmtpEmailService implements IEmailService {
    async send(to: string, subject: string, body: string): Promise<void> {
        // SMTP implementation
    }
}

export class MockEmailService implements IEmailService {
    async send(to: string, subject: string, body: string): Promise<void> {
        // Mock implementation for testing
    }
}

// Service depends on interface, not concrete implementation
export class CandidateService {
    constructor(private emailService: IEmailService) {}
    
    async create(data: CandidateData): Promise<Candidate> {
        const candidate = new Candidate(data);
        await this.emailService.send(candidate.email, 'Welcome', 'Welcome to LTI');
        return candidate;
    }
}
```

---

### Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)

Derived classes must substitute their base classes without breaking functionality.

```typescript
// Good: Subclass honors base contract
export class TemporaryCandidate extends Candidate {
    async save(repository: ICandidateRepository): Promise<void> {
        // Can be saved, like parent; just differ in behavior
        await repository.save(this);
    }
}

// Bad: Subclass violates parent contract
export class TemporaryCandidate extends Candidate {
    async save(): Promise<void> {
        throw new Error("Temporary candidates cannot be saved");  // Contract violation
    }
}
```

---

### Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)

Clients depend on specific, minimal interfaces, not fat interfaces.

```typescript
// Good: Segregated interfaces
export interface ISearchable {
    search(query: string): Promise<Candidate[]>;
}

export interface IPersistable {
    save(): Promise<void>;
}

export class CandidateService implements ISearchable, IPersistable {
    async search(query: string): Promise<Candidate[]> { /* ... */ }
    async save(): Promise<void> { /* ... */ }
}

// Bad: Fat interface forcing unnecessary implementations
export interface ICandidateService {
    create(): void;
    update(): void;
    delete(): void;
    search(): void;
    export(): void;
    import(): void;
    // ... many more methods
}
```

---

### Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)

High-level modules depend on abstractions, not low-level concrete implementations.

```typescript
// Good: Service depends on repository interface, not concrete Prisma calls
export class CandidateService {
    constructor(private candidateRepository: ICandidateRepository) {}
    
    async findById(id: number): Promise<Candidate | null> {
        return this.candidateRepository.findById(id);
    }
}

// Bad: Service depends on concrete Prisma client
export class CandidateService {
    constructor(private prisma: PrismaClient) {}
    
    async findById(id: number): Promise<Candidate | null> {
        return this.prisma.candidate.findUnique({ where: { id } });
    }
}
```

