## Database & Prisma Patterns

### Prisma Schema Design

**Single source of truth**: `prisma/schema.prisma` defines all database structure.

```prisma
model Candidate {
  id                Int       @id @default(autoincrement())
  firstName         String
  lastName          String
  email             String    @unique
  educations        Education[]
  workExperiences   WorkExperience[]
  createdAt         DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt         DateTime  @updatedAt
}

model Education {
  id                Int       @id @default(autoincrement())
  candidateId       Int
  candidate         Candidate @relation(fields: [candidateId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
  institution       String
  title             String
  startDate         DateTime
  endDate           DateTime?
}
```

**Best practices**:
- Use `@unique` for email fields to enforce database-level constraints
- Use cascading deletes (`onDelete: Cascade`) for owned entities
- Use `@default(now())` and `@updatedAt` for timestamps
- Include relationship fields (e.g., `candidateId`) alongside relations for query optimization

### Database Migrations

```bash
# Create migration after schema changes
npx prisma migrate dev --name add_candidate_educations

# Apply migrations in production
npx prisma migrate deploy

# Reset database (development only)
npx prisma migrate reset
```

**Guidelines**:
- Commit all migrations to version control
- Use descriptive migration names
- Review generated migration files before committing
- Never manually edit migration files

### N+1 Query Prevention

Always use `include` or `select` to fetch related data in one query.

```typescript
// Good: Fetches candidate with all related data in one query
const candidate = await this.prisma.candidate.findUnique({
    where: { id },
    include: {
        educations: true,
        workExperiences: true
    }
});

// Bad: N+1 queries (one for candidate, then N queries for educations)
const candidate = await this.prisma.candidate.findUnique({ where: { id } });
const educations = await this.prisma.education.findMany({ where: { candidateId: id } });
```

